Michelle didn’t attribute the last part to the changes her body had gone through over the last few days, though. Sure, the fact that work was easier was motivating, but it was still the same work that had gotten her down over the past weeks. Nothing had changed on that front. The true difference was that today, Michelle had something to look forward to. And it was ’t the possibility of drinking the super potion and the powers that came from it, either. She was anticipating something much more mundane, even though to her it was even more special than flying through the clouds was: a date. Saturday night, when she had been patrolling the city for the first time, she had envied the couples that were walking home together at that point. Michelle didn&rsquo;t miss the irony in that. In fact, she welcomed it. After all, the goal of finding love had been one of the few things that hadn&rsquo;t changed through getting these powers.
Amanda approached the hospital with a quick pace. Once her shift was over, she had practically run back to her apartment, changed out of her work clothes into something more appropriate. She hadn&rsquo;t dressed up too much: a green blouse, tight jeans and a pair of heels to make her appear taller. After all she was a proud woman worthy of being fought for, not a dumb girl that would fight for a lost cause. Now she walked through the halls of the hospital as if she owned the place. Amanda tried to ignore the fact that this was the place she had dreamed of working at long ago. This had been easier yesterday when she had entered Fred&rsquo;s room through the open window. Since she couldn&rsquo;t fly to the second floor this time, she had to take the stairs and finally the door. She knocked and entered to find a surprise.
Fred wasn&rsquo;t alone in his room, another man was standing in front of his bed. Amanda didn&rsquo;t know this guy, so it was unlikely that he was one of Fred&rsquo;s buddies. He was about the same age as them, tall and - Amanda had to admit - handsome.
&ldquo;A-Amanda,&rdquo; as expected Fred was totally surprised. &ldquo;What are you doing here?&rdquo;
&ldquo;That&rsquo;s my line. Erika told me that you&rsquo;re here, but she had no idea why you&rsquo;re here.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Welcome to the club,&rdquo; the other man interrupted. He put an end to her speculations by introducing himself. &ldquo;Hi, my name&rsquo;s James Thompson. I was just talking to Mr. Ryley about how he ended up here, as well. He claims to be run over by his own car, but I&rsquo;m not convinced this is everything.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Amanda Steward, nice to meet you.&rdquo;
So this was Michelle&rsquo;s date? Amanda couldn&rsquo;t deny her best friend&rsquo;s taste, but his presence here was a bit problematic.
&ldquo;So Mr. Ryley, would you like to tell us the whole story? I&rsquo;ve seen photos of your car and looks like someone had his way on it with a sledgehammer, not like it hit a human body.&rdquo;
&ldquo;You underestimate the damage, a human body can cause on a car,&rdquo; came Fred&rsquo;s answer.
Amanda almost started to laugh as she heard that. The truth was that she had kicked the car into the miserable state it was in now. In fact she hadn&rsquo;t even worn shoes as she had done that, so technically Fred wasn&rsquo;t even lying.
&ldquo;Yeah, the human body really is full of surprises sometimes, but your injuries don&rsquo;t match up with the accident you&rsquo;re describing. And even if you were hit by your own car as you describe, who drove it? Why did a woman call the ambulance but didn&rsquo;t wait until it arrived?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Why do you care? The whole thing was embarrassing enough, so why are you even more pressing than the cops about this?&rdquo; Fred actually had a point.
&ldquo;Because you&rsquo;re obviously hiding something,&rdquo; Amanda interrupted. She had come here with the intention of making Fred tell whatever he was hiding from her and she was going to see it through. It would only be suspicious if she suddenly supported him now. Now that she had a few seconds to think over it, if James was with the police, he may already know about Michelle’s actions. She might as well check out how much he knew.
James looked at her puzzled. Of course he hadn&rsquo;t expected her to side with him, but since he didn&rsquo;t know their history he quickly accepted her support. Then he answered Fred&rsquo;s original question.
&ldquo;The police and I have a different viewpoint when it comes to this situation. They only wanted to know whether or not they had to investigate a hit and run. But as long as you claim there was no crime involved - and you seem to have been quite convincing - their job is done. As for me, I&rsquo;m not looking for crimes but for scientifically relevant occurrences. The police tipped me of because they think your incident may be such a case.&rdquo;
Amanda watched Fred&rsquo;s expression intently. Despite his attempts to hide this fact, Amanda noticed her ex-boyfriend&rsquo;s irritation that she had sided with a total stranger against him. And since he clearly knew that she had every reason to be pissed at him, his irritation could only have one - much less rational - reason.
&ldquo;How exactly can this accident be scientifically relevant?&rdquo; Amanda decided to make sure she played her role as the one who knew nothing about Fred&rsquo;s incident. &ldquo;Even if it was a hit and run, that doesn&rsquo;t sound too interesting.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Yes, a strange hit and run wouldn&rsquo;t be that important, but I can connect Mr. Ryley to something that is scientifically relevant.&rdquo;
&ldquo;What?&rdquo; Both Amanda and Fred shouted in unison. Amanda was a bit relieved to see that Fred shared her surprise. Whatever he was hiding from her was rather normal after all.
&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t really understand this. What kind of occurrence can you connect me to?&rdquo; Fred asked.
&ldquo;Yesterday, there was a bank robbery,&rdquo; James began, only to be cut short by Fred.
&ldquo;You&rsquo;re hassling me just because my sister was the hostage in a bank robbery?&rdquo;
Amanda didn&rsquo;t like the sound of this. Had Erika been the hostage that Michelle had saved yesterday?
&ldquo;Did your sister tell you the whole story?&rdquo; The tone of James voice made it clear he assumed otherwise. To Amanda this just confirmed that James knew about Michelle&rsquo;s actions.
&ldquo;No, she was a bit pissed when I didn&rsquo;t tell her how &lsquo;this&rsquo; happened.&rdquo; Fred pointed at his knee.
James chuckled. &ldquo;I won&rsquo;t berate you on your communication issues, but you really missed an interesting story.&rdquo; He then turned to Amanda. &ldquo;You said you talked to her earlier. Did she mention anything?&rdquo;
Amanda shook her head. &ldquo;No, she didn&rsquo;t even mention that there was a bank robbery in the first place. What happened?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Something that you wouldn&rsquo;t believe if I told you. But since your boyfriend doesn&rsquo;t want to tell me how he broke his knee&hellip;&rdquo;
&ldquo;Ok, I get it!&rdquo; Fred blurted out. &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll tell you what happened if you tell me how that relates to my sister&hellip;&rdquo;
Fred then went on and told him about his encounter with &ldquo;Devil&rdquo;. He actually kept the description of Amanda&rsquo;s alter ego to a minimum, describing her only as a stunningly beautiful woman dressed only in a blue leotard. Amanda suspected that this description would be much more detailed if she weren&rsquo;t there. Now he even missed out her hair color - the main difference between her and Michelle in their super forms. James didn&rsquo;t seem to notice this fact. Other than that, Fred stayed true to the facts. Normally this would have been good news to Amanda. Any more lies would have made it much harder to even consider trusting her ex again. Unfortunately for her, the truth hurt. While it was heartwarming to hear that &ldquo;at that moment, Fred simply wasn&rsquo;t in the mood to flirt, not even with the most beautiful woman on earth&rdquo;, everything that followed was pure torture. Amanda had went over the whole situation many times in her head before, always coming to the conclusion that meeting Fred had already been the worst mistake back then. All the confidence about her new powers couldn&rsquo;t outweigh the anger she felt at him, thus causing her to lose her temper and ultimately hurting him. The problem was, that Fred didn&rsquo;t possess this piece of information. Due to this, Fred&rsquo;s version of her sounded more like a spoiled brat than a grown woman. And he didn&rsquo;t even do it on purpose.
&ldquo;She just started to trash your car? Just like that?&rdquo; James sounded quite shocked.
&ldquo;Well I wasn&rsquo;t really polite either,&rdquo; Fred answered.
&ldquo;That doesn&rsquo;t justify her actions. She stands on your car and talks about messing with you, who would stay polite after that?&rdquo; James turned to Amanda &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t you agree?&rdquo;
Amanda could only nod in reply. The question had taken her off-guard, but luckily she didn&rsquo;t need to speak or lie for this answer.
&ldquo;See? So how did she break your knee?&rdquo;
&ldquo;It was an accident, actually. She grabbed me by my shirt and flew up a bit. Then my shirt ripped, I fell and my knee didn&rsquo;t like the landing.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Why do I doubt that it was an accident,&rdquo; James thought aloud. Amanda didn&rsquo;t know what hurt more, the fact that this guy already hated her alter ego or the fact that she couldn&rsquo;t blame him.
&ldquo;Believe what you want, it was an accident!&rdquo; Fred surprisingly defended Amanda&rsquo;s alter ego. &ldquo;She didn&rsquo;t fake the concern when I fell, and she called the ambulance. If you ask me, she&rsquo;s just inexperienced with these powers.&rdquo;
Amanda hadn&rsquo;t expected this kind of support from the person who had every reason to hate her. She barely hid a smile even though she knew that her current role actually required her to act jealous of herself. Thankfully neither of the men noticed.
&ldquo;Anyway,&rdquo; Fred continued. &ldquo;Now that you know how I got injured, how about you tell me what&rsquo;s that got to do with my sister?&rdquo;
&ldquo;This woman has appeared a few times over the last few days, saving people from fire, rapists or in case of your sister: bank robbers.&rdquo; James sounded a bit disappointed as he said that. He took out his phone and began typing, eventually handing it over to Fred - who beckoned Amanda over to watch the screen together with him.
It was a video that showed the hostage situation Michelle had dealt with yesterday. It played out just as her best friend had described it, making it even harder for Amanda to act surprised. The only surprise for her was that Erika was indeed the hostage there. It was a total coincidence, but this was the reason James was here, after all. Amanda suddenly noticed Fred grabbing her hand. She looked at him only to see that he intently watched the events unfold. He hadn’t even noticed that he had grabbed Amanda’s hand and held it tight. When Erika was threatened at gunpoint, Amanda could feel him trembling on the inside. Seeing someone close to him in a life-threatening situation made him reach for any emotional crutch he could find. Amanda thought it would be tactless to mention now that Fred had lost his holding-hands-privileges during the breakup. In fact, she had her own problems watching the scenes and she had to constantly remind herself that Erika would survive the whole ordeal. When the bank robber finally dropped his gun, both Fred and Amanda let out a small sigh of relief.
Now Fred realized that he was gripping Amanda&rsquo;s hand and let go with an expression that was somewhere between embarrassment and thankfulness. He started the video again, this time without the tension. Then he paused it so that the freeze frame showed a decent view on Michelle&rsquo;s head and face. The video quality was awful, though.
&ldquo;It&rsquo;s not her,&rdquo; Fred finally exclaimed.
&ldquo;What do you mean? That was totally Erika!&rdquo; Amanda said this in a semi-serious tone. She already knew that Fred was about to clear a different misunderstanding.
&ldquo;The other woman, it&rsquo;s not the one I encountered.&rdquo;
&ldquo;How so?&rdquo; James asked.
&ldquo;The one I met was a redhead, this one seems to be blonde. It&rsquo;s be hard to recognize on this black and white video, but it seems like they also have different eye colors.&rdquo;
&ldquo;According to your sister she had quite remarkable blue eyes. And yes, she&rsquo;s blonde.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Then we&rsquo;re talking about two different women. The other one has orange eyes. She really looked like her eyes were on fire.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Two women with superpowers, huh?&rdquo; James let this revelation sink in.
Of course he was surprised, but Amanda noticed that he also seemed relieved to hear that. This was strange. Amanda had theorized about there being more than just the one plant that gave Michelle and herself superpowers and the possibility wasn&rsquo;t that encouraging.
&ldquo;You seem happy to hear that,&rdquo; Fred had noticed it too.
&ldquo;I know, the fact that there&rsquo;s more than one woman with superpowers should be quite scary, but try to see it this way: This blonde woman has shown up several times to help people - like a superhero so to speak. Would you prefer this woman to go around bullying people or would you rather have the bully being a totally different person? This way, Blondie could always step in if the redhead decided to cause real trouble.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Aren&rsquo;t you judging her too hard? So far it was just an accident, and she might become a superhero of her own.&rdquo;
James nodded, &ldquo;That might be even better, though the only way to find out for sure is to wait and see.&rdquo; Taking his phone back, he turned towards the door. &ldquo;Needless to say that, but I&rsquo;d really prefer you not to run to the next reporter talking about this. The media can turn this whole situation into a big mess if given the chance.&rdquo; With this he left.
Now that they were alone, an awkward silence followed. During James' presence they had acted as if everything was fine between them, but now it seemed like neither of them knew how to continue from here. It wasn&rsquo;t at all like Amanda expected it to be. Now that she officially knew about Fred&rsquo;s encounter with her alter ego, Amanda would have to pretend to be jealous - of herself. Not to mention the reason they had broken up in the first place: his cheating on her.
&ldquo;Thank you,&rdquo; Fred eventually said.
&ldquo;For what?&rdquo;
&ldquo;For coming here. It was more than I could ask for.&rdquo;
&ldquo;You may be right about that. But since Erika didn&rsquo;t know how you got injured, I feared it had anything to do with our breakup.&rdquo; The lies she had prepared beforehand came in handy after all. &ldquo;Doesn&rsquo;t seem this way, though.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Yeah, this woman came out of nowhere.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Really? From how you defended her, it sounded like you were quite fond of her.&rdquo; Amanda almost asked whether she was the one with whom he had betrayed her, but decided against it.
&ldquo;I won&rsquo;t deny that, after all she&rsquo;s the reason I wanted to talk to you in the first place.&rdquo; Fred was sounding more and more embarrassed as he said that.
&ldquo;How is that?&rdquo; For once, Amanda had absolutely no idea what he was getting to, and she feared that maybe he had figured out that she was &lsquo;Devil&rsquo;.
&ldquo;After the accident, she came visiting me here and apologized about the whole thing. She was really eager about that and I figured that I should follow her example.&rdquo; Fred took a deep breath. &ldquo;It was wrong of me to see another woman behind your back. I betrayed your trust and for that I&rsquo;m sorry. And if there&rsquo;s one thing I regret about the whole thing then it&rsquo;s the fact that I hurt your feelings. You were the one good thing in my life and I&rsquo;ll never forgive myself for hurting you.&rdquo;
Once again Amanda was amazed at how she instinctively knew that Fred was telling the truth here. As cliché as his words sounded, they were his true feelings. Yesterday it had been the same, but she had been in her super form back then. She had wondered if this was just another part of her powers, but right now she was normal. Without her powers, this instinctive trust was rather disturbing. Was she just fooling herself?
&ldquo;Why now?&rdquo; Amanda began. &ldquo;You had your chances to apologize before; I downright asked you if you had anything left to say yesterday. And you declined. So don&rsquo;t tell me that someone else actually needed to show you how to apologize.&rdquo; Amanda was getting louder and louder. &ldquo;Can you imagine how things look from my perspective? I tell you how it looked: It looked like you didn&rsquo;t care about our relationship at all, like nothing had any worth for you. I was just another stupid girl that fell for your lies. It&rsquo;s really hard for me to believe that you regret anything.&rdquo; Or at least it should be.
Fred didn&rsquo;t look into her eyes. Like a scolded boy he sat there and waited for Amanda to finish. He also waited a few seconds before he began his answer - seconds that seemed like eternity for Amanda.
&ldquo;Just because I didn&rsquo;t show any regret, it doesn&rsquo;t mean that I didn&rsquo;t have any. But I admit that I wasn&rsquo;t aware just how much all this meant to me. I knew my chances of patching things up were slim - and I suppose they still are. You&rsquo;re not the kind of woman that would simply forgive this whole affair. I wouldn&rsquo;t love you if you did. That&rsquo;s why I thought the best course of action would be a clean cut - the sooner we broke up, the sooner we would get over it and could continue with our lives.&rdquo;
&ldquo;So in other words, you gave up before the fight began? I thought you were more of an optimist. What about your affair herself? Where did she fit into your plan?&rdquo;
Fred sighed, naturally this was not his favorite topic. &ldquo;Honestly I didn&rsquo;t have one, as I had no particular feelings for her.&rdquo;
&ldquo;No particular feelings?&rdquo; Amanda almost shouted. &ldquo;Then why did you have this affair in the first place?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Because she had … connections. There&rsquo;s more than one reason for me not to be proud of this, but the truth is that I used her. I wanted to get something and this affair was the best - well, actually the only - way to get it.&rdquo;
Amanda didn&rsquo;t believe what she heard. &ldquo;Let me ignore how cliché this sounded, what exactly did you want to achieve through her?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Since it was me who betrayed your trust, I can&rsquo;t allow myself to lie to you if I want us to get back together. But this is something I don&rsquo;t want you to know. This is too private.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Did I hear this right? You want to make up with me but you want to hide the very reason you cheated on me? How much more selfish can you get? I mean how am I supposed to trust you at all?&rdquo;
&ldquo;I already told you why I cheated on you! All I left out is one detail that I consider too personal for this. Do you really think this detail could make the circumstances any worse?&rdquo;
There was something in Fred&rsquo;s voice that disheartened Amanda. He was losing hope about getting back together. After all she hadn&rsquo;t given him any hint that this might work. Perhaps letting him hold her hands and being here in the first place were too subtle for him to notice, not to mention that he didn&rsquo;t have any clue that she felt guilty for his knee.
&ldquo;I suppose not,&rdquo; Amanda said, calming herself down. &ldquo;But it&rsquo;s a bit hard to imagine a relationship together if you&rsquo;re going to keep secrets from me.&rdquo;
&ldquo;I prefer the term privacy; after all I don&rsquo;t know every tiny detail about you either. Some things need time to build up the necessary trust and this is one of them.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Could you at least tell me that it&rsquo;s not something illegal?&rdquo;
&ldquo;I&rsquo;m a jerk, not a criminal.&rdquo; Fred forced himself to chuckle, only to contort his face in pain - his knee didn&rsquo;t like to be moved yet. He then asked the question that tortured them both for the last day. &ldquo;Do you believe there&rsquo;s a future for us?&rdquo;
&ldquo;I doubt things will become exactly the same as before. But I also can&rsquo;t deny the fact that I want things to work out between us as well.&rdquo; Fred&rsquo;s face clearly lightened up upon hearing this. &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t get me wrong, this isn&rsquo;t a free pass for you. We&rsquo;ll take things slowly and you will have some concessions to make of your own.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Like what?&rdquo;
&ldquo;For example I&rsquo;m going to need my share of privacy as well&hellip;&rdquo;
The closer evening came, the more Michelle&rsquo;s anticipation was replaced by panic. It began with her eating an early dinner only to remember that her date included dinner in the first place. For a second she wondered if this was some kind of withdrawal symptom as she hadn&rsquo;t been normal for such a long time since her first transformation. But that wasn&rsquo;t the case. Sure the idea of drinking the potion and transforming into her superpowered alter ego was as tempting as always, but it wasn’t like she really needed it. No, she had been eating because she was nervous &hellip; and hungry, but that was to be expected. Now she was standing in the shower, trying to get her nervousness under control by thinking about the irony of the situation. Two days ago she had been sure that her next date would be in her super form with her super powers as the ultimate confidence boost. It turned out she could score herself a date just fine even without them. Well… almost. The tiny improvements to her body had helped as well and while she still had no idea how deep these improvements went, she already added heightened sensitivity to the list – the hot water on her skin really felt good. Her super self on the other hand was turned on by the other sex in unexpected ways: by their fists and bullets from their guns. The latter with unexpectedly erotic results. There had been only one instance that could be considered flirting and that was a teenage boy she had saved from a mugging last night. The boy had blatantly asked if he had died and gone to heaven – given the fact that he had been threatened at gunpoint before Michelle’s intervention, he might have believed what he said. Why was such a kid even out at night?
Stepping out of the shower she took a look at the time and learned that she had been showering for almost forty-five minutes. Great, now she had only fifteen more minutes left until James would arrive. In a hurry she began to dry herself. Good thing she had already planned out her outfit for the night: a beautiful red dress that hadn’t fit too well earlier as well as matching red heels. The dress had been a birthday present from Amanda, so instead of changing it, Michelle had intended to lose the few pounds that would make the dress a perfect fit – and she had lost those pounds after transforming back to normal. The shoes were a present from her sister for the same birthday – since she lived in another town, she clearly had cooperated with Amanda. Normally Michelle wasn&rsquo;t the type to wear heels, but today was a special occasion. With the time running short, she didn&rsquo;t have any time to stand around worrying. Ten minutes later she was finished and gave her mirror image a final check. God she looked great. She filled out the dress as if it had been bought specifically for this evening. Her face looked absolutely gorgeous even though she wasn&rsquo;t even wearing any make-up. Only one thing seemed off, but Michelle couldn&rsquo;t figure it out. Since she managed to be ready before her date arrived, she took a final look at her bedroom to check if there was some evidence she needed to hide. The plant was still hidden in plain sight on her nightstand, since it would only be suspicious to conceal something like this. She spotted her over-sized flip-flops on the floor and proceeded to hide them in her closet along with the other clothes she had bought for her super self. Michelle had long since taken care of any trace of the potion in her room. Her supply was hidden in the fridge and she checked once more for any glass or vial she had used to transform - only to confirm that she had indeed washed all of them. Then she noticed her glasses that laid unused on her nightstand.
&ldquo;Oh my god,&rdquo; Michelle whispered to herself. She hadn&rsquo;t even noticed that she had forgotten to put on her glasses because she had no trouble seeing. With shaking hands she tried to put them on. As her vision got blurry she immediately took them back off. It was official: she wasn&rsquo;t near-sighted anymore. As great as that was, why did it have to happen now, right before a ding dong date? No use in fretting over it now. As she headed to the door, she took one last glance at the mirror. Brown. At least the color of her eyes was still as it should be. As she walked to the door she felt herself getting nervous again and she calmed herself down that being in better condition than expected couldn&rsquo;t be a bad thing. Once she had opened the door, her nervousness had all but disappeared. James had taken things just as seriously as she, and Michelle had to admit that he looked great in a suit. He really looked like a guy that could walk into a bar and leave it with a woman in each arm - if it weren&rsquo;t for the dumbfounded look on his face that made it really obvious that he liked what he saw. Who needed superpowers as a confidence boost if she could render a handsome guy like him speechless?
&ldquo;Wow … uhm, I mean hi.&rdquo; James' face turned bright red as he struggled for words. He cleared his throat before finally making any decent sense. &ldquo;Sorry about that, I was just astounded by how great you look.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Thank you. You look nice as well,&rdquo; Michelle said with the most charming smile. She wasn&rsquo;t nervous anymore. This was going to be fun.
Amanda looked around the bar Erika had dragged her to. It was still early in the evening, so there weren&rsquo;t many customers besides them. Erika had arrived at Fred&rsquo;s hospital room shortly after he and Amanda had agreed to give their relationship another chance. She quickly accepted this turn of events, but she seemed a bit wary about it as well. Things turned a bit awkward when Fred and Erika exchanged their stories about their encounter with Super Amanda and Super Michelle. Like James before, Erika didn&rsquo;t really have a high opinion about Super Amanda. She became understandably irritated that her brother seemed to defend the woman who was responsible for his condition. Especially in front of his girlfriend. Fred used this opportunity to explain how this incident had given him a second chance with Amanda, causing the latter to exclaim that she was right there. Thankfully the discussion then shifted more towards Erika&rsquo;s role as a hostage and Michelle&rsquo;s intervention about it. When Amanda excused herself to leave, Erika had surprisingly accompanied her &lsquo;to have a chat&rsquo;.
Now they were sitting in a booth at a bar waiting for their drinks. Amanda wondered about Erika&rsquo;s motivation - fearing that the other woman had drawn the painfully obvious conclusion that the &ldquo;evil redhead&rdquo; had acted far too much like a pissed ex-girlfriend not to be suspicious about Amanda and him making up afterwards. On the other hand, Amanda had a few questions for Erika as well. Whatever it was that Fred was hiding from her, Erika was the only person besides himself that might know about it. Once again, Amanda noticed the tired look in Erika&rsquo;s eyes. Considering what the other woman had been through, this was absolutely understandable.
&ldquo;I have to admit I&rsquo;m a bit surprised that you actually showed up at the hospital, not to mention forgiving him,&rdquo; Erika began. &ldquo;Actually, I thought you were too proud to overlook something like this. What changed your mind?&rdquo;
